I‚Äôm sure its part of the reason why % of minority employees *decreases* over time on the corporate ladder. In addition to the work there is a layer of psychological stress from ‚Äúmaking it‚Äù

BTW no shots fired at Publicis for these %s. Other holdcos straight out refused to share. https://t.co/PQ1tLCQ3Vo

This is just one of the things that most corporate environments don‚Äôt get when a majority of employees come from wealth. 

Those that don‚Äôt (usually minorities) face this level of cognitive dissociation every day, and it gets tougher up the latter. Guilt, imposter syndrome, etc.

‚ÄúThe way you answered suggests that you feel a sense of guilt for taking advantage of the privileges that this company is relying on you use to be effective at what you do.‚Äù 

Essentially: Never apologize for flying Business Class when conducting business.

Part of the process was taking a personality test. 

The person conducting this section was African American. As per usual, I was one of the only non-white employees in this training session. 

At the end of the day he pulled me aside and flat out told me: ‚ÄúStop feeling guilty.‚Äù

A year later, my holdco put some young managers into a training program called ‚ÄúBest Athlete‚Äù that was about balancing your whole life to maintain peak performance at work. 

It was progressive and I was probably too young to really appreciate it. Here‚Äôs one of the charts: https://t.co/BXZ1shvits

A business coach later told me: 

‚ÄúYou have to think of yourself as an athlete. You‚Äôre not playing sports, but you are playing a game that will constantly stress your body and mind. Take advantage of every benefit and privilege that your company gives you with this in mind.‚Äù

This was one of those situations where I got reprimanded for doing what I thought was right. The difference in fare was close to $10K. 

He said ‚Äúthe value of you being awake and alert in that room is worth more than the difference in price. You need to sleep on that plane.‚Äù

Earlier in my career (I was 32 at the time), I was sent to Paris for a project where I‚Äôd have to take a red eye from NYC and go straight to the office for a presentation.

I booked Economy bc I wanted to be a good employee and save $. An MD ordered me to change to Business Class.

Shifting between House of Brands vs Branded House as a strategy for new brand/category rollout. 

It makes sense. Had never thought of brand architecture serving that purpose, because it‚Äôs always been either/or. Interesting to think about. https://t.co/iDpRZ70Vxv

If you have to fly a lot, doing it in economy 100% of the time will wreck your body (and your mind if you do it enough). 

Also ignores free loyalty upgrades. 

If you‚Äôre *that* important, upgrading yourself once in a while is an investment in efficacy, health, and longevity.
‚ÄúI‚Äôm rich and/or important but fly economy‚Äù is the weirdest virtue signaling flex.
